<paragraph blockId="21.[189,1399,1807,2010]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[189,497,1807,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Simosyrphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandicornis">
<emphasis box="[189,497,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Simosyrphus grandicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has often been confused with species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sack" authorityYear="1913" box="[964,1080,1807,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ischiodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[964,1080,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Ischiodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryan" authorityYear="1934" box="[1216,1361,1807,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Ischiodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellaris">
<emphasis box="[1216,1361,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">I. scutellaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as they are sympatric and the males of both species have large genitalia. The morphological characteristics to distinguish 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[377,569,1878,1904]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Simosyrphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandicornis">
<emphasis box="[377,569,1878,1904]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">S. grandicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the broadly rounded basoflagellomere (subacute apically in 
